---
import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import PageHeader from '@/components/ui/PageHeader.astro';
import MerkleTreeExplorer from '@/components/react/MerkleTreeExplorer.tsx';
import ValueTable from '@/components/ui/ValueTable.astro';
import Formula from '@/components/ui/Formula.astro';
import Callout from '@/components/ui/Callout.astro';
import DocRef from '@/components/ui/DocRef.astro';
import { MID_TABLE } from '@/data/tables';
---
<BaseLayout
  title="Merkle tree explorer"
  description="Authenticating OSNMA public keys with a Merkle tree, on real test-vector data."
>
  <PageHeader
    eyebrow="4 · Cryptographic machinery"
    title="The Merkle tree"
    lead="A single stored root authenticates any of sixteen public keys, using only a short path of sibling hashes carried on the signal."
  />

  <p>
    OSNMA could ship a fresh certificate for every public key, but that is heavy
    over a 40-bit channel. Instead it commits to all of its public keys at once
    with a <strong>Merkle tree</strong> <DocRef doc="icd" section="6.2" />. The
    receiver stores just the 256-bit root. To prove a key, the signal carries the
    key plus four sibling hashes; the receiver climbs to the root and checks the
    match.
  </p>

  <h2>How the tree is built</h2>
  <p>Each public key becomes a leaf, hashed, then internal nodes hash their two children:</p>
  <Formula tex="m_i = \text{NPKT} \,\|\, \text{NPKID} \,\|\, \text{NPK}" display />
  <Formula tex="x_{0,i} = H(m_i), \qquad x_{j,i} = H\big(x_{j-1,2i} \,\|\, x_{j-1,2i+1}\big)" display />
  <p>
    With 16 leaves the tree is four levels deep, so any leaf is authenticated by
    exactly four sibling nodes — the <em>intermediate tree nodes</em> (ITN) in the
    DSM-PKR.
  </p>

  <h2>Verify a real key</h2>
  <p>
    The walkthrough below uses the actual <code>Merkle_tree_1</code> material from
    the official test vectors: the real public key for leaf 0 and the real sibling
    nodes. Step through the climb and watch the recomputed root land on the
    published value.
  </p>

  <MerkleTreeExplorer client:visible />

  <Callout type="tip">
    <p>
      The recomputation runs live in your browser with SHA-256. It reproduces the
      official root bit-for-bit — the same success criterion a receiver uses to
      accept a public key from a DSM-PKR.
    </p>
  </Callout>

  <h2>Which siblings for which leaf</h2>
  <p>
    The DSM-PKR's <strong>MID</strong> field says which leaf is being delivered and,
    implicitly, which four siblings travel with it <DocRef doc="icd" section="3.2.2.2" />.
  </p>
  <ValueTable table={MID_TABLE} />

  <Callout type="note">
    <p>
      Because the tree commits to all keys in advance, key renewal does not need a
      new out-of-band trust anchor: a new key simply arrives as another
      authenticated leaf. The tree itself changes only on a multi-year horizon.
    </p>
  </Callout>
</BaseLayout>
